        The strs are the row headers
        n and m are column headers 
               m=0 1 2 3 4 5 || n=0 1 2 3 
        10
        0001
        11001
        1
        0
        >> think of the row headers as all permutations of m and n 
            >> [m,n] = 00, 01, 02, 03, 10, 11, 12, 13, 20, 21, 22, 23 etc. 

        each cell represents the maximum form using strs with a max m and n in the row headers
            >> for row 0 you can only use strs[0]
            >> for row 1 you can use strs[0] and strs[1]
            >> for row 2 you can use strs[0], strs[1], and strs[2] 
            >> and so on
        So this couples the rows to the previous row. 
            >> for each new row we are populating, we choose to either (1) NOT use the strs[row] or 
                (2) Use strs[row] 
                >> (1) If we do not use strs[row] then we just retrieve dp[row -1][colM][colN]
                >> (2) If we use strs[row] then we dp[row][colM][colN] = dp[row-1][colM-countM][colN-countN] + 1
                    >> countM and countN are the counts of 0's and 1's for strs[row] respectively
                    >> Hence we have to check if colM-countM >=0 and colN-countN >= 0 otherwise
                        dp[row][colM][colN] = case(1) because we it means you do not have enough available 0's or 1's 
