# Identification of Problem
Let's start by figuring out what's given to us and how we can use it.
We're provided with an vector of strings as input and two integers m and n which denotes maximum number of 0's and 1's the subset of string can have!

1. We have a choice whether to include a string or not in the subset.
2. We have been asked about finding largest subset i.e. optimal condition

So, we have a choice and we've to give optimal condition in output. Generally, these problems of choice and optimal condition is solved using... 

YES! you've guess it **Dynamic Programming!**

# Identification of parent problem statement
This is the most important part of dynamic programming whether if we're able to identify the parent problem set.

Here, we've given a vector of stings as input

```
strs= ["10", "00001", "1110001", "1", "0"]
m=5, n=3
```
We have an condition that it should have at most m-> 0's and n-> 1's.

Let's draw the choice diagram for a better understanding of the problem.

![photo_2023-06-10_02-16-32.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e012fdf9-ed13-46cb-a0ef-335bb0774954_1686343610.8904438.jpeg)

In short, we can say

![photo_2023-06-10_02-18-28.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/9faa95cf-7d84-4b5e-83d2-f0356ad28fbd_1686343718.8429286.jpeg)

> If number of 0's in string is **greater than m** or **number of zeroes greater than n** we can't include the string as it's not satisfying the condition.
If **number of 0's in string is less than or equal to m** or **number of zeroes less than equal to n**, we have to choice to include the string in the solution or not.

**From this we can identify this problem is similar to 0/1 Knapsack!**
Why? Let's again see it through choice diagram of 0/1 knapsack.

![photo_2023-06-10_02-24-26.jpg](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/165e9a8b-cab8-4db3-9251-8074c9aea7f5_1686344107.1137526.jpeg)

**But, there is only one array given in this problem statement in knapsack problems there are two arrays one weight and other profit!**
When the problem has same choice diagram as knapsack but there is only one array given consider it as weight array and do the changes.

# Code for general 0/1 Knapsack:
```
int knapSack(int W, int wt[], int val[], int n) 
    { 
       if(n==0 || W==0) return 0;

       if(wt[n-1]<=W)
        return max(knapSack( W,wt,val,n-1 ) , val[ n-1 ] + knapSack( W-wt[n-1],wt,val,n-1 ) );

       return knapSack( W,wt,val,n-1 );
    }
```

# Modified Knapsack code for this solution:
```
1. Calculate number of zeroes and ones in the string.
2. Think of base condition here if the index equals the size of the 
   given vector or when value of m and n both equals zero we return 0.
3. Modify the knapsack code!
```

```
class Solution {
public:
    int noZeros(string s){
        int count =0;
        for(char ch: s){
            if(ch== '0' )count++;
        }
        return count;
    }

    int noOnes(string s){
        int count =0;
        for(char ch: s){
            if(ch== '1' )count++;
        }
        return count;
    }

    int helper(vector<string> & strs, int m, int n, int ind){
         // Base Condition
        if(ind ==strs.size() || (m==0 && n==0)) return 0;

        // Calcualte number of ones and zeros in the string
        int zeros=noZeros(strs[ind]);
        int ones=noOnes(strs[ind]);

        int choose= 0;
        if( zeros <= m && ones <= n ){
            return max( helper( strs, m, n, ind+1), 1 + helper( strs, m-zeros, n-ones, ind+1));
        }
        return helper( strs, m, n, ind+1);
    }

    int findMaxForm(vector<string>& strs, int m, int n) {
        return helper(strs, m, n, 0);
    }
};

```

