**Disclaimer : This post is for beginners who are new into problem solving and are looking for detailed explainations, so it is written that way. Cheers.**

If we see this problem at first we might consider that this can be solved by greedy, Frankly I tried solving it that way. Because it was passing most of the test cases that i tried. Even after submission it passed 63 testcases out of 71. But sadly 🥲🥲 🥲🥲  this approach does not work. So if you are like me who explore different option & is trying to go in this path and need some counter example, this post is for you or you can directly skips to approach 1 where i have explained building blockes of actual solution.


Approach that I was thinking is as under.

like if we have m zeros and n ones, then the maximum size of subset could be m+n in best case. If input string have m string of length 1 with zero as value and n string of length 1 and 1 as value.

So it make sense to sort the input array by length and elements with same length can be sorted by difference of ones and zeros. Now we pick elements from left to right if they can be added.

Code 

```
class Solution {
    public int findMaxForm(String[] strs, int zeros, int ones) {
      List<String> inputStrings = new LinkedList<>(Arrays.asList(strs));

      Collections.sort(inputStrings,(m,n)->{

          if(m.length()<n.length())
              return -1;
          else if(m.length()>n.length())
              return 1;
          else {
              int oneM=0,oneN=0;
              oneM = countOne(m);
              oneN = countOne(n);

            int zeroM = Math.abs(m.length()-oneM);
            int zeroN = Math.abs(n.length()-oneN);

              int differenceM = Math.abs(oneM-zeroM);
              int differenceN = Math.abs(oneN-zeroN);

          if(differenceM<differenceN)
              return -1;
          else if(differenceM>differenceN)
              return 1;
          else
              return 0;
          }

      });  

      int count=0;
     System.out.println(inputStrings);

      for(int i=0;i<inputStrings.size();i++) {
          int countofone  = countOne(inputStrings.get(i));
          int countofzero = inputStrings.get(i).length()-countofone;
          if((zeros-countofzero)>=0 && (ones-countofone)>=0){
             count++;
             zeros= zeros-countofzero;
             ones = ones-countofone;
          } 
      }  


      return count;  
    }

    public int countOne(String input){
        int count=0;
        for(int i=0;i<input.length();i++) {
                  if(input.charAt(i)=='1'){
                      count++;
                  }
              }
        return count;
    }
}
