solutions.content:
This question can be solved like a 0/1 knapsack. 
In classic 0/1 knapsack we use 2-D matrix for DP, here we use a 3-D matrix.
If you understand classic 0/1 knapsack, this question would be a cakewalk.
NOTE : Here I used DP matrix of 3 dimension for simplicity, but same can also be solved a using a DP matrix of 2 dimension.

**Steps -**

1) Make a n*2 matrix comp which stores number of zeros and ones in a string .
```
for(int i=0;i<strs.size();i++)
{
	for(int j=0;j<strs[i].size();j++)
	{
		if(strs[i][j]=='0')
			comp[i][0]++;    
	}
	comp[i][1]=strs[i].size()-comp[i][0];
}
```


2) Now create 3 nested for loops for strs.size(), m, n respectively and fill DP as shown below.


```
for(int i=0;i<=strs.size()++)
{
	for(int j=0 ; j<=m;j++)
	{
		for(int k=0;k<=n;k++)
			if(i==0)
				dp[i][j][k]=0;
			else if(j>=comp[i-1][0] && k>=comp[i-1][1])
			{
				dp[i][j][k]=max(dp[i-1][j][k],1+dp[i-1][j-comp[i-1][0]][k-comp[i-1][1]]);
			}
			else
				dp[i][j][k]=dp[i-1][j][k];
	}   
}
```
3) return dp[strs.size()][m][n];


Upvote if it helped a bit : )

